  "doc_id": "52874",
  "text": "notropic polypeptide (GIP) levels. GIP is a gut hormone that is secreted from enteroendocrine K cells, which are predominantly located in the intestinal epithelium of the proximal duodenum [CITATION_1] . The secretion of GIP is stimulated by the access of secretagogues such as dietary fat, carbohydrates, and proteins to the luminal surface of K cells [CITATION_2] . The primary action of GIP is to potentiate glucose-stimulated insulin secretion from pancreatic ␤-cells. In addition to pancreatic ␤-cells as the classical target of GIP, the GIP receptor (GIPR) is located on various extrapancreatic organs, including adipose tissue [CITATION_3] . Previous studies demonstrated that GIP mediated various anabolic effects on adipocytes, including the stimulation of glucose uptake [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , lipoprotein lipase (LPL) activity (19 -21) , and fatty acid synthesis [CITATION_6] . Furthermore, recent studies in mice implicated GIP in the regulation of energy metabolism and subsequent obesity-related phenotypes [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The prevention of high-fat diet-induced obesity accompanied by increased fat utilization has been observed in genetically GIPR-ablated mice [CITATION_11] . Furthermore, a daily injection of the specific GIPR antagonist, (Pro3)GIP, to high-fat diet-fed obese mice resulted in a decrease in body weight and adipose tissue mass accompanied by improvements in insulin sensitivity and the normalization of glucose tolerance [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] .",
